rgatory by means of their personal interventions. The text also bears witness to female friendship, effective intergender dialogue, and the central role played by an anchoress in those communities with which she interacted, be they spiritual, institutional or personal. Liz Herbert McAvoy is Professor of Medieval Literature at Swansea University.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPurgatoryxEarly works to 1800. 4aHistory of Religion. 4aMedieval Literature. 4aWomen's & Gender Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aAnchoress.  aRevelation.  afemale author.  afemale.  agender studies.  ahistory.  aliterature.  amedieval history.  amiddle ages.  apurgatory.  areligion.  atranslation.  avisions.1 aMcAvoy, Liz Herbert, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311143130740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781787440555?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781787440555423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781787440555/original  a978-3-11-143130-7  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles